definition: "Vitamin A is a group of fat-soluble retinoids that includes retinol (the primary form in animal-sourced foods and supplements), retinal, and retinoic acid. Retinol is the storage and transport form measured in blood; it circulates bound to retinol-binding protein (RBP). Retinoic acid — the biologically active form — functions as a ligand for nuclear receptors (RARs and RXRs) that directly regulate gene transcription, controlling the expression of hundreds of genes involved in cell growth, differentiation, immune function, and embryonic development. Provitamin A carotenoids (beta-carotene, alpha-carotene, beta-cryptoxanthin) from plant foods can be converted to retinol by the intestine, though conversion efficiency varies widely between individuals. The body maintains serum retinol within a narrow range through a feedback system that releases vitamin A from liver stores as needed — serum retinol remains stable until liver reserves are substantially depleted (in deficiency) or until stores are massively overwhelmed (in toxicity). This buffering makes serum retinol a relatively insensitive marker of mild-moderate changes in status, though it remains the standard clinical measurement."
why_it_matters: "Vitamin A sits at an unusual position in nutritional medicine: it is among the most important micronutrients for immune function, cellular differentiation, and epithelial barrier maintenance, while also being the most toxic of the fat-soluble vitamins when consumed in excess over time. Both extremes accelerate biological aging and increase all-cause mortality, but through different mechanisms. Deficiency impairs mucosal barriers (the first line of immune defense), reduces natural killer cell activity and antibody production, disrupts the cellular differentiation needed for tissue maintenance and repair, and is a leading preventable cause of blindness globally. Chronic vitamin A toxicity — most commonly from long-term high-dose supplementation, particularly preformed retinol from supplements or fortified foods — causes liver damage, reduced bone mineral density (through increased osteoclast activity), hypercalcemia, and teratogenic effects. Multiple large supplementation trials have found that high-dose vitamin A supplementation increases lung cancer risk in smokers and may increase all-cause mortality at doses that were once considered safe — a finding that substantially changed the supplementation landscape. For most longevity-focused adults, the goal is adequacy without excess: ensuring reserves are not depleted, while being cautious about long-term supplementation."

standard_range: "20–100 μg/dL (serum retinol)"
