longevity_notes: "The standard clinical range for serum retinol extends to 100 μg/dL, but values above 80 μg/dL in an adult taking supplements are worth reviewing — not because they necessarily indicate toxicity, but because they suggest liver stores may be building toward the range where long-term adverse effects become relevant. The upper tolerable intake level for preformed vitamin A (retinol) is 10,000 IU/day for adults; chronic intakes above this threshold are associated with bone and liver adverse effects. Importantly, provitamin A carotenoids from food (beta-carotene in vegetables) do not cause hypervitaminosis A — the body down-regulates conversion when stores are adequate. Synthetic beta-carotene supplements, however, have shown adverse effects in smokers and should be avoided."
