faqs:
- question: "Should I be testing vitamin A regularly if I take a multivitamin?"
  answer: "It depends on the dose of preformed vitamin A in your multivitamin. Many standard multivitamins contain 2,500–5,000 IU of preformed retinol (or a combination of retinol and beta-carotene). At these doses with a reasonably balanced diet, vitamin A status is unlikely to become dangerously elevated in a person with normal liver function. However, some multivitamins and dedicated vitamin A supplements provide 8,000–10,000 IU or more — approaching the tolerable upper intake level. If you take a supplement containing above 5,000 IU of preformed retinol daily, or if you eat large amounts of liver regularly (beef liver contains ~6,500 μg of retinol per 3-oz serving, far exceeding daily needs), a periodic serum retinol measurement is reasonable to confirm you're not building toward toxic accumulation. For people on standard-dose multivitamins eating a varied diet, routine vitamin A testing is lower priority than vitamin D or other commonly deficient nutrients."
- question: "I eat a plant-based diet — am I at risk for vitamin A deficiency?"
  answer: "Plant foods do not contain preformed retinol — they contain provitamin A carotenoids, primarily beta-carotene. Whether these carotenoids are efficiently converted to retinol depends significantly on individual genetics (specifically BCMO1 gene variants), diet composition (fat in the same meal substantially improves carotenoid absorption), and gut health (malabsorption reduces conversion). Some studies suggest that a meaningful proportion of people — possibly 20–45% — are 'poor converters' of beta-carotene to retinol due to BCMO1 polymorphisms. For people following a strict plant-based diet who are also poor converters, vitamin A deficiency is a real risk. If you eat no animal products (which are the only dietary source of preformed retinol), serum retinol testing is a reasonable baseline check — particularly if you also have any gastrointestinal absorption issues."
- question: "What conditions cause vitamin A deficiency even with adequate dietary intake?"
  answer: "Several conditions impair vitamin A absorption or increase requirements beyond what diet can supply. Fat malabsorption conditions (celiac disease, Crohn's disease, cystic fibrosis, short bowel syndrome, cholestasis, pancreatic insufficiency) reduce absorption of fat-soluble vitamins including vitamin A. Bariatric surgery — particularly malabsorptive procedures like Roux-en-Y gastric bypass — significantly increases the risk of fat-soluble vitamin deficiency including vitamin A. Zinc deficiency impairs retinol-binding protein synthesis and vitamin A mobilization from the liver, creating functional vitamin A deficiency even when liver stores are adequate. Chronic heavy alcohol consumption depletes vitamin A liver stores through multiple mechanisms. In any of these contexts, routine vitamin A monitoring is clinically indicated."
- question: "What are the early signs of vitamin A toxicity?"
  answer: "Acute vitamin A toxicity from a single massive dose (unlikely outside accidental ingestion of polar bear or seal liver, which are extraordinarily rich sources) causes nausea, vomiting, dizziness, and headache within hours. Chronic vitamin A toxicity from sustained high-dose supplementation has more insidious onset: early signs include dry, rough, or peeling skin; hair loss; fatigue; headaches; and joint and bone pain. With progression, liver damage (hepatomegaly, elevated liver enzymes, and eventually fibrosis), pseudotumor cerebri (elevated intracranial pressure causing headaches and visual changes), and reduced bone mineral density with increased fracture risk develop. Toxicity symptoms can appear at supplemental intakes of 25,000 IU/day over months to years, and more gradually at lower doses. Stopping supplementation usually leads to gradual improvement in early toxicity, though liver damage from prolonged high-dose intake may not fully reverse."

